children’s verse, Orme does a masterful job of recovering a lively and largely unknown tradition, preserving the playfulness of the originals while clearly explaining their meaning, significance, or context. Poems written in Latin or French have been translated into English, and Middle English has been modernized. Fleas, Flies, and Friars has five parts. The first two contain short lyrical pieces and fragments, together with excerpts from essays in verse that address childhood or were written for children. The third part presents poems for young people about behavior. The fourth contains three long stories and the fifth brings together verse relating to education and school life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aChildren's poetry, English (Middle)vTranslations into English. 0aChildren's poetry, FrenchzGreat BritainvTranslations into English. 0aChildren's poetry, Latin (Medieval and modern)zGreat BritainvTranslations into English. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aPOETRY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChildren's Poety from the Middle Ages.  aChildren's poetry.  aEnglish childhood in the Middle Ages.  aMedieval anthology.  aMedieval art.  aMedieval children's verse.  aMedieval children.  aMedieval culture.  aMedieval education.  aMedieval england history.  aMedieval england.  aMedieval history.  aMedieval literary criticism.  aMedieval lullabies.  aMedieval nursery rhymes.  aMedieval poems for children.  aMedieval poems.  aMedieval poetry.  aMedieval social history.  aMedieval traditions.  achildren's studies.  aenglish Medieval history.  aenglish middle ages.  amiddle ages children.  amiddle ages history.  arenaissance literary criticism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z97831105361